A shooting at Westroads Mall in Omaha left eight dead, including the shooter, Robert A. Hawkins.
The incident, described as random and unprovoked, shocked the nation.
Hawkins, troubled and depressed, left a note expressing remorse before taking his own life.
Victims included employees and customers, with several injured.
President Bush, who had been in Omaha earlier, expressed condolences.
The tragedy highlighted the prevalence of gun violence in the United States.
The community mourned the senseless loss as authorities investigated the motive behind the deadly rampage.
